{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17503471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17503471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:01:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:01:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2034"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2034"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.62,0.06,0.07,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98559"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2034","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2034"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2034"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80955"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1028"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4370"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11215"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33789"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42437"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98559"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with an ongoing history of episodes of torticollis, blepharospasm, right hand weakness and loss of sensation in her left foot. She experiences an episode weekly. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She has been feeling low because of these symptoms. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination findings are non-specific and an extensive workup including magnetic resonance imaging was unremarkable. Whilst she has a good job, she has not attended work in the past six months because of these symptoms and her partner is concerned. Despite her symptoms, she has been able to maintain her hobbies doing arts and crafts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Functional neurological symptom disorder","Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease","Illness anxiety disorder","Malingering"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture described in this question suggests a diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Efunctional neurological symptom disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (formerly known as conversion disorder). Functional neurological symptom disorder involves the following: \u003Cbr /\u003E1. One or more symptoms of altered voluntary motor or sensory function \u003Cbr /\u003E2. Clinical findings showing incompatibility between the symptom/s and recognised neurological or medical conditions \u003Cbr /\u003E3. These symptoms or deficits are not better explained by another medical or mental health disorder \u003Cbr /\u003E4. The symptom/s cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social, occupational, or other important areas of functioning that warrants medical attention \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EFunctional neurological symptom disorder is a diagnosis of exclusion. It requires detailed history taking and a thorough neurological examination, as well as laboratory and neuroimaging tests to rule out an organic cause for the patient\u0027s symptoms. It is important to keep in mind that a history of depression, anxiety and panic attacks are common in patients with functional neurological symptom disorder. While it is always important to look for psychological stressors, the \u0022trigger\u0022 is not always obvious at first assessment and the absence of an obvious \u0022trigger\u0022 does not rule out the diagnosis. Neuroimaging tests may include CT and MRI, although in some cases CT angiogram or MR angiogram may also be indicated. Electroencephalogram (EEG) may also be helpful to rule out seizure activity. \u003Cbr /\u003E\u003Cbr /\u003EThe most successful and evidence based treatment of functional neurological symptom disorder is multidisciplinary inpatient treatment, conducted by a team including rehabilitation specialists and psychologists. There is also some evidence for cognitive behavioural therapy and hypnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E: While the relapsing-remitting form of MS could seem similar, in MS the onset and duration of symptoms is more often days to weeks, the episodes less regularly frequent and after a duration of more than six months of symptoms severe enough to be unable to work one would expect neurological signs on examination and at least MRI signs of patchy demyelination. However, MS is a great imitator and does need careful exclusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the various forms of \u003Cstrong\u003ECharcot-Marie-Tooth disease\u003C/strong\u003E torticollis and blepharospasm are not features and one would expect to find neurological signs of peripheral neuropathy including sensory loss and muscle atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIllness anxiety disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by persistent, anxious preoccupation with the idea of having an illness in the absence of somatic symptoms (or at least with only minor symptoms). In an allied disorder, somatic symptom disorder, the somatic symptoms (often pain) are prominent and a focus for persistent anxious thinking and behaviour.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn \u003Cstrong\u003Emalingering\u003C/strong\u003E, there is a deliberate, conscious and intentional production of exaggerated symptoms where the motivation is external gain (financial, status, avoidance, legal etc). This motivation is usually obvious once the situation is understood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Functional neurological symptom disorder does not always have an apparent psychological stressor or \u0027trigger\u0027.","Functional neurological symptom disorder is characterized by neurological symptoms incompatible with recognized neurological conditions.","Diagnosis of functional neurological symptom disorder requires exclusion of organic causes through thorough clinical assessment and investigations."],"references":["Tsui P, Deptula A, Yuan DY. Conversion Disorder, Functional Neurological Symptom Disorder, and Chronic Pain: Comorbidity, Assessment, and Treatment. Current Pain and Headache Reports. 2017;21(6):29."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80955"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2034"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80955","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80955"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-14T19:01:53+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-14T19:03:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2034"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98559"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":